  "response_text": "The metric representing the total number of times agents selected whole milk demonstrated a consistent and statistically significant upward trend throughout the simulation. Starting from an initial value of 0.0000 at time step 0, the metric rose to a final value of 2194.5667 by time step 32. The average value across the entire series was 1130.8818, with the median recorded at 1158.9667. No local peaks or valleys were identified, indicating a monotonic progression without reversals. The statistical analysis confirmed an increasing trend with high significance (p=0.027) across all evaluated rolling windows, with a slope generally ranging between 64.067 and 76.199. This continuous accumulation reflects the persistent influence of strong initial habits (parameter set to 10) and the cumulative nature of the metric, which aggregates repeated consumer choices over time rather than measuring instantaneous preference levels. The growth remained relatively linear without significant structural changes, suggesting that the parameters for social influence and habit retention resulted in a steady baseline adoption of whole milk across the agent population."
}

